About one in four women say that the dissolution of a relationship represents one of the biggest obstacles to raising children on their own, according to results of a common research study titled “Women in the public space” undertaken the Centre for the Research of Ethnicity and Culture (CVEK) for OZ Viva, a civic association.

At Storytelling Films, we have been helping to make the lives of women easier since 2005, with the aim of advancing gender equality and combatting negative stereotypes in order to improve the lives of women in both Slovakia and the UK.

Main protagonists: women themselves.
Scientists, politicians, scientists, pundits, and other scientists

The woman-centred events and public discussions that we organise are designed to give women a chance to speak their minds on issues that are important to them. Some of these events are broadcast on national television stations, with the aim hosting a live debate and exchanging of points of view — a tradition that is so rare in contemporary Slovakia.

For instance, in the year 2008, CVEK organised a forum devoted to improving the conditions for raising children on their own in Slovakia. This particular discussion sparked controversy because it was aired on private television. During the discussion, there were of accusations of censorship and the discussions between political representatives were fierce.
